Notes: Pulled discharge, pH, and water chemistry data from another publication, Greenwood and Rosemond (2005) in Canadian Journal of Fisheries and Aquatic Science. Hal assumed litter C:N was reported as molar, given molar was also mentioned for dissolved N:P ratios in the paper. The C:N and raw data were challenging to pull from figures, so Hal placed the cursor on the fitted lines to get C:N means at each date, instead of measuring each of the individual symbols (replicates) on each date separately. Hal only pulled mean K-values from Fig 1 for this reason.The pre-treatment YR 1 data did not include C:N of the litter, so these data were not included.

Notes: Study in ponds. Manipulated mesh size and collected invertebrates. Measured phenolics as well, but its expressed per unit C mass, so can't be converted to mass percent. Initial litter amounts in bags reported as wet mass only. Extracted N content of litter from figure and converted to molar C:N. Mass loss expressed as % initial C remaining. I was little surprised by the high C:N of the initial litter, but I double checked my conversion calculation is correct. pH was derived from average of reported ranges for each site.

Publication_Title: Litter decomposition of six macrophytes in a eutrophic shallow lake (Baiyangdian Lake, China)
Notes: Study did not note whether macrophytes were living or dead when collected for decomposition. Only that the plants were standing "intact". Measured decomposition of different tissues from various macrophytes. Reported ratios appeared to be mass (based on %C/%N calculations) so converted to molar but left ratio type as NA because not stated in paper. Coordinates appear to be for the correct region but does not match the lake shown in Fig. 1. Plant P (and water TP) analysed via ICP with no comment on digestion

Publication_Title: Wetland plant decomposition under different nutrient conditions: what is more important, litter quality or site quality?
Notes: The condition of detritus when it was initially deployed was standing dead shoots. Four plots were established in each marsh in August of 2001, one represents a control, the remaining three received N, P and NP addition once in August2001 and the second time in August2002. N was added as ammonium nitrate and P as triple super phosphate in the amounts corresponding to 20 and 10 g m 2 y 1, respectively. Six treatments - control litter in control C. NP litter in control NPC. P litter in P plot P. N litter in N plot N. NP litter in NP plot NP and control litter in NP plot CNP. Lots more CNP data but are aggregated across salinity treatments

Publication_Title: Wetland plant decomposition under different nutrient conditions: what is more important, litter quality or site quality?
Notes: %C appears to be calculated from molar CN ratios, not included in raw extraction file.

Litter breakdown and invertebrate association with three types of leaves in a temperate rainforest stream
Notes: Water from Mayfly Creek was diverted into experimental stream channels - 14m long and about 25 cm wide with a slope of approximately 0.03m/m. Leaf packets were placed in mesh boxes inside of the channels. Mesh size was 0.48 mm except for the upstream side where the mesh size was 1mm. On the upstream side of the mesh box was a 2 cm opening that also allowed invertebrates to move in and out of the box. Nutrient values were analyzed only in two times: d0 and d39 /d43. I did not collect data on water variables because they are from another study in another year (1979).

Elevated CO2 induced changes in the chemistry of quaking aspen (Populus tremuloides Michaux) leaf litter subsequent mass loss and  microbial response in a stream ecosystem
Journal: Journal of the North American Benthological Society
Notes: Populus tremuloides were grown under both elevated (720 ppm) and ambient (360 ppm) levels of atmospheric CO2. The experiment was run for 30 days, with only one removal to assess the decomposition (30 days later). For CN, samples were taken after 5, 10, 15, 20, 25 and 30 days. K values were corrected after a leaching experiment (not collected). The remaining dry mass values were not corrected. Microbial community respiration was reported.

Rapid breakdown of allochthonous and autochthonous plant material in a eutrophic river
Geog_Locale: Snake River, Twin Falls, Idaho, USA
Notes: The objective of this study was to determine whether differences existed between decomposition of autochthonous macrophytes (breakdown measured in spring and fall) and allocthonous litter (breakdown measured only in July). Water chem: Converted mg/L SRP to ug/L. No initial mass provided; paper says leaves were divided into samples, but does not report how much in each bag. Authors report sample size of "three to four bags"- I note only the more conservative number since they do not specify.

Publication_Title: Silicon controls microbial decay and nutrient release of grass litter during aquatic decomposition
Notes: polyethlene test vessels hold 3 L water. Unclear where test vessels were kept during the experiment. Manipulation=phragmites grown in elevated silica, and shredder manipulation (gammarus addition). SRP concentrations seem exceptionally low and with high precision (all <2.000 ug/L), but reported in Fig. 2. Decomp experiment was run for 6 weeks.  Leaf litter mentioned in methods, used that for Detritus_Type. Water chemistry was tracked in the beakers throughout experiment. Cellulose, lignin and phenols not significantly different before/after experiment among treatments (but were measured both before/after so included here). Table 3 appears to include CNP data for before/after, but doesn't appear consistent with CNP data given in Table 2? I used Table 2 values for Si- Si+ as starting values for associated treatments, and Table 2 values for ending values for all 4 treatments.

Publication_Title: Silica decouples fungal growth and litter decomposition without changing responses to climate warming and N enrichment
Notes: Start date ~early December 2009. study site described as 'littoral marsh' of Lake Hallwil. Altitude estimated from google earth. % mass loss data included for Phragmites sheaths and culms too (included only leaf blade data here because this is what litter chem data were from). For temp and nitrate data, used monthly data from Dec (beginning) and April (end of leaf blade decomp). Initial mass 0.8-1.1 g (recorded as "1" in the data here)

Notes: Data reported also for dissolved total phosphorous (DTP), particulate phosphorous (PP) and dissolved organic phosphorous (DOP); TP and SRP concentrations are corrected by evaporation loss; before starting the experiment (day 1) plants were incubated with lake water <24h (no mass reported); Initial_Mass_g=100g fresh weight (not reported in DW); Fig. 8 axis for C:P and N:P are the same. I think for C:P are wrong, so I not use these values; Geog_Locale and lat_long for macrophytes sampling site; Authors should have pH for each sampling points, but not reported. They say "The pH gradually decreased from neutral (7.10  0.35) at the beginning of the experiment to slightly acidic values (6.10  0.31) at the end"

Publication_Title: Effects of nitrogen and phosphorus availability on the decomposition of aquatic plants
Notes: E. crassipes was collected  as dead green leaves when leaved died due to frost  (I called detritus condition: "green"); V. natans  were collected as dead green leaves in Augsut (I called detritus condition: "senesced") and P. maackianus were colected live green leaves in october (I called detritus condition: "green") Leaf litter that was dried at 85 C for 48 h before experiment; Soluble sugar % initial values are reported; Incubations at the dark house at the Laboratory of Aquatic Plants I stated light_category="shaded", the quality of the figures is not very good and it's difficult to extract data, the concentrations of P and N are from the medium formula preparated in the lab (that were new every week), however I'm not sure if ammonium and ntirate concentrations are correct because they differ from a previous experiment (Xie, 2004_hydrobiologia) and seems a similar setting. I've found an issue with the initial litter chemistry litter: C:N and C:P calculated and extracted (weight) only matches for E. Crassipes! To do the calculations for %N, %P during the incubations I will use the initial %N and %P reported in the Table (and not the reported ratios!). k only reported in the text for some cases, I leave NA the ones is not reported (or reported as intervals since not difference found among nutrient treatments)
